## How it works — step by step

| Step | What happens |
|------|--------------|
| **Request arrives** | Fetch `timestamps` array for the client IP (empty if first visit) |
| **Slide the window** | `findIndex` locates the first timestamp `> now - windowMs`; everything before it is discarded |
| **Count** | If `timestamps.length >= maxRequests` → **429**; return without calling `next()` |
| **Allow** | Push `now` onto the (now-pruned) array, write back to the Map, set the three headers, call `next()` |
| **Cleanup tick (60 s)** | Iterate the Map; delete any IP whose *newest* timestamp is older than `windowMs` |

### Headers set on allowed requests

| Header | Value |
|--------|-------|
| `X-RateLimit-Limit` | `maxRequests` |
| `X-RateLimit-Remaining` | slots left in the current window |
| `X-RateLimit-Reset` | Unix epoch **second** when the oldest in-window request expires |

### 429 response

```json
{ "error": "Rate limit exceeded", "retryAfter": 42 }
```
Plus `Retry-After: 42` (seconds until the earliest slot opens).

### Why this is a *true* sliding window

A fixed-window limiter resets a counter at clock-aligned intervals (e.g. every full minute). This means a client can fire `maxRequests` at 0:59 and another `maxRequests` at 1:01 — 2× the limit in two seconds. This implementation never resets; it continuously evicts timestamps older than `windowMs` **relative to right now**, so the allowed burst is always bounded by exactly `maxRequests` in any `windowMs`-length interval, no matter when it starts.

